summarization.model_original_answer: The study develops a medication direction generation and evaluation system, MEDIC, to improve the accuracy and safety of medication directions. MEDIC uses a three-stage process: rule-based formatting, AI-powered extraction, and safety guardrails. It is trained on a dataset of 1.6 million single-line medication directions and evaluated on a test set of 20,000 prescriptions. The system is compared to two benchmarks, T5-FineTuned and Claude, and found to be more accurate and safer. MEDIC's safety guardrails reduce near-miss events by 33% and increase suggestion coverage by 18.3%. The system is integrated into pharmacy operations, leading to a 44.3% decrease in post-adoption edits and a 28.5% increase in suggestion adoption.

summarization.model_original_answer: The study aims to determine the upper limits on the luminosity of quasar host galaxies at high redshifts. To achieve this, the authors use a method of subtracting the point spread function (PSF) from the quasar images to obtain the galaxy flux. They find that the PSF-subtracted images of the quasars J1340+2813 and J0731+4459 show no obvious PSF patterns and radial profiles consistent with an n=1 Sérsic profile only at low flux levels. By adjusting the normalization of the PSF, they determine the upper limits on the galaxy flux. The authors also use the IRAC Band 1 fluxes of galaxies at similar redshifts to establish an empirical relationship between the 3.6 μm flux and galaxy mass, which they use to constrain the masses of their quasar host galaxies. The results suggest that the host galaxies are not massive enough to follow the local black hole-galaxy mass relation, implying that the relation may not be applicable at high redshifts.
